Data Gathering

If you can work with Dutch postal codes and numbers, you can utilize a premade dataset that combines the pchnr6 from cbs.nl, enriched with geolocations. Below are the first 10 rows of the dataset. The full dataset contains nearly 8 million entries.

dataframe <-PDOK::cbs_pchn6_geo()
dataframe <- dataframe[dataframe$coordinates!="error",]
print(dataframe[c(1:10),])

If you do not work with Dutch postal codes and numbers, you can find the coordinates for your own entries. For example, here is how you can find the coordinates of Amsterdam:

options(digits = 10)
amsterdam <-PDOK::pdok_find_coordinates(input="amsterdam")
## [1] "amsterdam Coordinates: 52.36648685, 4.91978668"
amsterdam <-  as.numeric(unlist(strsplit(amsterdam, ",")))


Data Wrangling

To calculate the distance between our point retrieved in Amsterdam and the geolocations in our dataset we use geosphere package and calculat ethe distance as shown below. We then calculate there are around 330k entries found within 10km in our dataset. At last I take 10 random adresses within 10 km radius for our upcoming visual.

dataframe <- dataframe %>%
  mutate(
    lat = as.numeric(sapply(strsplit(coordinates, ","), "[", 1)),
    lon = as.numeric(sapply(strsplit(coordinates, ","), "[", 2))
  )

dataframe <- dataframe %>%
  mutate(
    distance_km = distHaversine(matrix(c(lat, lon), ncol = 2), amsterdam) / 1000
  )

dataframe %>% filter(distance_km<= 10) %>% summarize(n=n())
random_sample  <- dataframe %>% 
  filter(distance_km<= 10) %>%
  sample_n(10)


Map Making

We now use the Leaflet package in R to make an interactive map where we showcase the points of the 10 random adresses within our dataset. You can zoom the visual if you want.

m <- leaflet() %>%
  addTiles() %>%
  addMarkers(
    lng = random_sample$lon, 
    lat = random_sample$lat, 
    popup = random_sample$corrected_point
  )

m

We can then add the central point of Amsterdam we got by calling the query. We separate it from the other markers by making it a red circle marker. We then draw lines from the other points to our central and show the distance to each point.

m <- leaflet() %>%
  addTiles() %>%
  addMarkers(
    lng = random_sample$lon, 
    lat = random_sample$lat, 
    popup = random_sample$corrected_point
  ) %>%
  addCircleMarkers(
    lng = amsterdam[2], 
    lat = amsterdam[1], 
    popup = "Point", 
    color = "red",
    radius = 5,
    fillOpacity = 1
  )

for (i in 1:nrow(random_sample)) {
  point <- random_sample[i, ]
  distance <- distHaversine(c(point$lon, point$lat), c(amsterdam["lon"], amsterdam["lat"])) / 1000  # Distance in km
  
  m <- m %>%
    addPolylines(
      lng = c(point$lon, amsterdam[2]),
      lat = c(point$lat, amsterdam[1]),
      color = "blue"
    ) %>%
    addPopups(
      lng = (point$lon + amsterdam[2]) / 2,
      lat = (point$lat + amsterdam[1]) / 2,
      popup = paste0(round(random_sample$distance_km[i], 2), " km")
    )
}


m
